te quite clearly that the curriculum doesn't encourage independent thought and incentivizes &quot;teaching to the test'. &#10;If schools had more freedom to explore subjects more widely, you might have a point, but in recent years there has been greater and greater central control. Can it really be good thing that everybody has to stick to the same narrow state-prescribed curriculum in schools? Can this be described as conducive to independent thought? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="737" language="en" documentId="920" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="HJHJ" date="06 November 2009 4:04pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6745302" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="920" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="19"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="20" end="244"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="245" end="405"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="406" end="737"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>